TY  - JOUR
T1  - Fragmented Property Rights and Incentives for R&D
AU  - Clark, Derek J.
AU  - Konrad, Kai A.
Y1  - 2008/05/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1080.0873
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1080.0873
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 969
EP  - 981
VL  - 54
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Where product innovation requires several complementary patents, fragmented property rights can limit firms' willingness to invest in R&D. We consider the research intensity in multiple simultaneous R&D contests and how it depends on whether firms already hold relevant patents as well as the availability of an option to invent around. A measure of technological uncertainty is also analyzed. The multiple patent product involves an important hold-up problem that can reduce the overall R&D effort. Invent-around options moderate this problem. We also analyze targeted equilibria in which the aim of R&D can be to hold up a rival.
